1. Introduction

The dataset used in this notebook is from University of California at Irvine (UCI) Repository. The student performance data contain math, and portuguese language data. We will at the mathematical performance of students in this notebook.

1.1 Data Dictionary

school - student's school (Categorical: GP = Gabriel Pereira, MS = Mousinho da Silveira)

sex - student's sex (Categorical: F = female, M = male)

age - student's age (numeric)

address - student's home address type (Categorical: U = urban, R = rural)

famsize - family size (Categorical: LE3 = less or equal to 3, GT3 = greater than 3)

Pstatus - parent's cohabitation status (Categorical: T = living together, A = apart)

Medu - mother's education (Categorical: 0 = none, 1 = primary education (4th grade), 2 = 5th to 9th grade, 3 = secondary education or 4 = higher education)

Fedu - father's education (Categorical: 0 = none, 1 = primary education (4th grade), 2 = 5th to 9th grade, 3 = secondary education or 4 = higher education)

Mjob - mother's job (Categorical: 'teacher', 'health' care related, civil 'services' (e.g. administrative or police), 'at_home' or 'other')

Fjob - father's job (Categorical: 'teacher', 'health' care related, civil 'services' (e.g. administrative or police), 'at_home' or 'other')

reason - reason to choose this school (Categorical: close to home, school reputation, course' preference or other)

guardian - student's guardian (Categorical: mother, father or other)

traveltime - home to school travel time (Categorical: 1: <15 min., 2: 15 to 30 min., 3: 30 min. to 1 hour, or 4: >1 hour)

studytime - weekly study time (Categorical: 1 - <2 hours, 2 - 2 to 5 hours, 3 - 5 to 10 hours, or 4 - >10 hours)

failures - number of past class failures (numeric)

schoolsup - extra educational support (Categorical: yes, no)

famsup - family educational support (Categorical: yes, no)

paid - extra paid classes within the course subject (Categorical: yes, no)

activities - extra-curricular activities (Categorical: yes, no)

nursery - attended nursery school (Categorical: yes, no)

higher - wants to take higher education (Categorical: yes, no)

internet - Internet access at home (Categorical: yes, no)

romantic - with a romantic relationship (Categorical: yes, no)

famrel - quality of family relationships (Numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - excellent)

freetime - free time after school (Numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)

goout - going out with friends (Numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)

Dalc - workday alcohol consumption (Numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)

Walc - weekend alcohol consumption (Numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)

health - current health status (Numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - very good)

absences - number of school absences (Numeric: from 0 to 93)

G1 - first period grade (Numeric: from 0 to 20)

G2 - second period grade (Numeric: from 0 to 20)

G3 - final grade (Numeric: from 0 to 20, output target)

3.1.3 Some insights we can gather from these graphs¶
  • Most of this data contains students from Gabriel Pereira (GP).
  • There is roughly an even distribution of students by gender.
  • Age is skewed to the right. This is not out of the ordinary as it isn't common to see people being high school students beyond age 18 as they would have graduated by then.
  • Most of this data shows students live in an urban area. This follows through as most of the data are made up of students from GP, which is located in the city.
  • Family sizes are on average greater than three.
  • Most students have parents that live together.
  • Parents' education is mostly equal. More women are university educated, and more men are 5th to 9th grade educated.
  • Most guardians are mothers.
  • Most students study in between 2 to 5 hours.
  • Family and educational support, as well as extracurriculars, are roughly split 50/50.
  • Most students aspire to reach higher education.
  • Internet access is available for most students.
  • Most students rate themselves as having a good health, however there are quite a lot of students who do not rate their health as good.

3.2.4 Some insights we can gather from the data¶
  • Median final grades higher in GP (11) in comparison to MS (10).
  • Median final grades are slightly higher in male students.
  • Urban students have a higher median final grade compared to rural students.
  • Final grades are roughly equal between family sizes greater than, or less than, 3.
  • Study time leads to higher grades, though people that study between 5-10 hours and 10 or more hours yield don't have much different in academic performance.
  • People that don't have extra school support do better than those without, and the inverse is true with respect to family support.
  • Students that do extracurricular activity have slightly higher final grades than those that don't.
  • Students who aspire for higher education have higher grades than those that don't.
  • Students with internet access to slightly better than those that don't have internet access.
  • Students not in a romantic relationship do slightly better than those that don't.

Conclusions¶

  • Urban students do slightly better than rural students. This could be since living in an urban environment gives one more access to resources (such as tutors, etc).
  • Study time leads to higher grades, but those that study in between 5-10 hours or more than 10 leads to equal grades. It could be that studying more until a certain point levels off the potential grades you can earn. A student could be overstudying, and is no longer gaining as much from studying.
  • Students that have extra school support don't do as well as those that don't. Unsure of how exactly this can be, but given this insight, it could be the school support system is working to the detriment of the students that use it.
  • Students with family support have higher grades than those that don't. Having family on your side can ease stress and allow students to perform better.
  • Students that do extracurriculars do better than those that don't. It could be that those students being more involved with the school are also more motivated to do better in school than others.
  • since higher education requires higher grades, it makes sense to see students who aspire for higher education, do better than those that don't.
  • Having internet access is a huge, and mostly, necessary, advantage than those that don't. The internet has free resources on any subject that a student can access within seconds.
  • Romantic relationships require time. Since high school students aren't as experienced in time management, if they are in romantic relationships, they spend less time studying than those that don't, and the more you study, the better you end up performing.
  • Absences are not correlated well with grades. However, most of the data on absences is right skewed - meaning most of the students in the data are not absent a whole lot. Unless we can get more data on students that are absent, we can't make good conclusions based on this part of the data.
